WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.220 --> 00:00:03.010
FEMALE SPEAKER: Please join me
in welcoming to Google New

00:00:03.010 --> 00:00:04.480
York, Alex Guarnaschelli.

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:05.420
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Thank you.

00:00:05.420 --> 00:00:06.670
Thank you.

00:00:08.710 --> 00:00:10.850
Do you love my homey
that I brought in

00:00:10.850 --> 00:00:11.510
the front row texting?

00:00:11.510 --> 00:00:14.210
How are you?

00:00:14.210 --> 00:00:14.860
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's right.

00:00:14.860 --> 00:00:16.910
We got a lot of people here
that are psyched.

00:00:16.910 --> 00:00:19.550
So at Google, passion is huge.

00:00:19.550 --> 00:00:21.600
We are passionate people.

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:24.510
We take on passionate
projects.

00:00:24.510 --> 00:00:28.610
And I was curious as to how
you turned, and when you

00:00:28.610 --> 00:00:32.590
turned, your passion for food
and cooking into a career.

00:00:32.590 --> 00:00:33.610
What triggered it?

00:00:33.610 --> 00:00:36.172
What triggered the passion even
before it was a career, I

00:00:36.172 --> 00:00:38.620
should say?

00:00:38.620 --> 00:00:40.410
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Well, I
would say that I'm not a

00:00:40.410 --> 00:00:45.850
terribly organized person, and
that I don't really think

00:00:45.850 --> 00:00:48.960
things happen that clearly.

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:51.590
My mother cooked with
wild abandon.

00:00:51.590 --> 00:00:53.330
My mother's a cookbook editor.

00:00:53.330 --> 00:00:57.250
And I know we're no longer in
an age where books are the

00:00:57.250 --> 00:00:58.970
most relevant form
of information.

00:00:58.970 --> 00:01:01.290
But when I was growing
up they really were.

00:01:01.290 --> 00:01:05.700
And my parents are two nerdy
academics that met while they

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:08.580
were getting their respective
PhDs at Yale.

00:01:11.450 --> 00:01:15.680
My dad got his PhD in European
history specializing in

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:18.660
Napoleonic warfare
and was a TA.

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:21.710
And my mother was getting a
PhD in Russian studies.

00:01:21.710 --> 00:01:24.330
You can't make this stuff up.

00:01:24.330 --> 00:01:27.150
So my mother conveniently speaks
fluent Russian just in

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:29.980
case anything goes down.

00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:36.050
And my father knows more about
Napoleon than Napoleon did.

00:01:36.050 --> 00:01:37.620
So they met.

00:01:37.620 --> 00:01:40.780
They got married at Yale.

00:01:40.780 --> 00:01:43.970
Suffice to say, you can imagine
that books were kind

00:01:43.970 --> 00:01:46.010
of an important thing.

00:01:46.010 --> 00:01:46.960
So they got married.

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:51.170
And I grew up in a very
big nine-room

00:01:51.170 --> 00:01:53.220
apartment in midtown.

00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:57.370
It's rent-controlled, people.

00:01:57.370 --> 00:01:59.500
My dad told me the rent they
pay the other day.

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:00.733
And I just kind of twitched.

00:02:00.733 --> 00:02:02.050
FEMALE SPEAKER: Oh, god.

00:02:02.050 --> 00:02:03.420
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: But
they deserve it.

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:04.410
FEMALE SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:02:04.410 --> 00:02:06.720
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: So my
mother had 1,000 books.

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:07.790
My dad 1,000 books.

00:02:07.790 --> 00:02:09.350
You multiply that
by 80, and you

00:02:09.350 --> 00:02:10.630
have my parents' apartment.

00:02:10.630 --> 00:02:14.160
So I grew up in a place
where my wallpaper was

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:15.300
bookshelves and books.

00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:18.180
And I think that that has a
profound effect on you or

00:02:18.180 --> 00:02:20.350
consciousness, whether you
realize it or not, when you

00:02:20.350 --> 00:02:22.890
run around the apartment where
you live and there's nothing

00:02:22.890 --> 00:02:24.060
but books and manuscripts.

00:02:24.060 --> 00:02:27.580
And my mother's process for
editing a cookbook was to take

00:02:27.580 --> 00:02:30.860
the manuscript and cook every
single recipe in it.

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:35.150
The consequence, or the result,
was in 1980 when she

00:02:35.150 --> 00:02:39.070
started really delving
into cookbooks.

00:02:39.070 --> 00:02:42.290
She did a cookbook called
"Classic Indian Cooking."

00:02:42.290 --> 00:02:45.690
So that cookbook came out
30, 32 years ago.

00:02:45.690 --> 00:02:48.050
It's still in print.

00:02:48.050 --> 00:02:49.160
I mean, what?

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:54.120
A black-and-white Indian
cookbook with no photographs?

00:02:54.120 --> 00:02:56.480
You can still buy it at
Barnes and Noble.

00:02:56.480 --> 00:02:58.890
I go and I look for it.

00:02:58.890 --> 00:03:00.610
I'm like, I'm going to Barnes
and Noble just to see if that

00:03:00.610 --> 00:03:01.540
book is sitting on the shelf.

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:04.030
I'm not going to buy it.

00:03:04.030 --> 00:03:07.660
So we spent a year eating Indian
food, which was very

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:11.140
confusing because I'm
Italian American.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:13.030
And my father loves Napoleon
and France.

00:03:13.030 --> 00:03:14.590
And my mom was making
all these souffles.

00:03:14.590 --> 00:03:17.080
And then all of a sudden we were
eating lentils and dals

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:19.260
and spices and all this stuff.

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:24.240
And my father doesn't really
care for Indian food because

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:28.580
it doesn't have any butter
or eggs, so to speak.

00:03:28.580 --> 00:03:31.030
So he called it the
mowed lawn phase.

00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:34.160
He said that everything tasted
like a freshly mowed lawn.

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:35.990
Which I really disagree with.

00:03:35.990 --> 00:03:36.970
FEMALE SPEAKER: I disagree.

00:03:36.970 --> 00:03:38.450
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: So that
was an interesting year.

00:03:38.450 --> 00:03:40.600
And then the year after that,
she did a book called "The

00:03:40.600 --> 00:03:43.590
Splendid Table," by Lynne
Rossetto Kasper, which was the

00:03:43.590 --> 00:03:44.780
food of Emilia-Romagna.

00:03:44.780 --> 00:03:49.550
So for a year, we went from
lentils and dals to balsamic

00:03:49.550 --> 00:03:52.480
vinegar and parmigiano
reggiano ad nauseum.

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:55.250
My father said, if I see another
drop of balsamic

00:03:55.250 --> 00:03:57.640
vinegar in this house,
I'm leaving.

00:03:57.640 --> 00:03:59.950
She then did a book called
"The Cake Bible,"

00:03:59.950 --> 00:04:01.980
by Rose Levy Beranbaum.

00:04:01.980 --> 00:04:05.670
So that was not good because
that was really an elastic

00:04:05.670 --> 00:04:06.920
waist year.

00:04:09.150 --> 00:04:11.450
And the thing about my mother
is all the while there was

00:04:11.450 --> 00:04:16.209
this other pulsating
undercurrent of reading and

00:04:16.209 --> 00:04:19.079
cooking from issues of "Gourmet"
magazine that she

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:20.920
had bound into binders.

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:24.350
I think my mother has 30 years
of "Gourmet" bound in books.

00:04:24.350 --> 00:04:27.930
So she would make a cake from
Rosy Levy Beranbaum's "Cake

00:04:27.930 --> 00:04:33.710
Bible," and then make a pie from
a 1974 November issue of

00:04:33.710 --> 00:04:38.910
"Gourmet" magazine and say,
do you feel that this cake

00:04:38.910 --> 00:04:40.930
relates to this pie at all?

00:04:40.930 --> 00:04:42.740
How do you think pie
has changed?

00:04:42.740 --> 00:04:43.990
I'm 13.

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:53.200
This was just really practice
for "Chopped." I mean, it's

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:54.240
funny, I know.

00:04:54.240 --> 00:04:58.960
But it's also insanely true.

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:00.350
The fork was in the air.

00:05:00.350 --> 00:05:03.172
And my mom would say,
how does it taste?

00:05:03.172 --> 00:05:05.800
So there was never just a moment
of eating that was just

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:06.880
sort of like--

00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:08.530
and let's get this
out of the way.

00:05:08.530 --> 00:05:10.150
I love Doritos.

00:05:10.150 --> 00:05:10.980
I love Oreos.

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:12.750
And I love Fruit Loops.

00:05:12.750 --> 00:05:15.990
I also really love ice cold skim
milk, Fruity Pebbles, and

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:18.500
a scoop of Haagen-Daz chocolate
chocolate chip in

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:19.930
the middle of it.

00:05:19.930 --> 00:05:22.440
So let's get the junk
food out of the way.

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:23.880
I like junk food.

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:27.390
And I'm cool with that.

00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:29.640
So there was just this constant
interview process.

00:05:29.640 --> 00:05:32.120
So she cooked from all
these manuscripts.

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:35.440
And guess what happens when you
are an editor and you go

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:37.690
through a book and you cook
everything in it and you edit

00:05:37.690 --> 00:05:38.580
it that way?

00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:42.160
You wind up with a great book
because it's been sort of

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:44.620
lived through the
editor's eyes.

00:05:44.620 --> 00:05:48.790
And the net result is that my
mother has been behind many

00:05:48.790 --> 00:05:53.070
iconic cookbooks, including the
1997 revision of "The Joy

00:05:53.070 --> 00:05:55.300
of Cooking," which my
mother took on.

00:05:55.300 --> 00:06:00.440
And that, she spent three
years doing, sleepless.

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:03.160
I was working at Restaurant
Daniel at the time.

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:04.270
And he used to serve lunch.

00:06:04.270 --> 00:06:07.500
So I would get up at 4:00 and
go to the restaurant to be

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:11.100
there by 4:30, 5 o'clock.

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:12.440
I'll talk about what
I ate when I worked

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:14.930
at Daniel in a minute.

00:06:14.930 --> 00:06:18.620
So I would get up and she would
be still up, with her

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:20.920
glasses off, you know, this
close to the manuscript.

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:23.130
And I'd say, what's up?

00:06:23.130 --> 00:06:28.190
And she'd say, does this look
like a Malpeque oyster or not?

00:06:28.190 --> 00:06:29.590
And she'd showed me a drawing
of an oyster.

00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:31.830
So we'd go back to that moment
with the pie, the cake, the

00:06:31.830 --> 00:06:32.990
comparisons.

00:06:32.990 --> 00:06:35.860
There was never a moment
where it wasn't a quiz.

00:06:35.860 --> 00:06:37.030
And I said, you know,
it looks a little

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:37.860
round around the edges.

00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:39.375
It looks a little Blue
Point, if you ask me.

00:06:39.375 --> 00:06:40.625
What?

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:44.110
The next day, mom,
how are you?

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:46.320
Does this look like
a Belgian waffle?

00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:49.190
Three years of that.

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:52.590
The result is that that book
also has really endured, that

00:06:52.590 --> 00:06:55.220
particular edition of "The Joy
of Cooking." So needless to

00:06:55.220 --> 00:06:58.550
say, I spent a childhood steeped
in food in a very

00:06:58.550 --> 00:06:59.750
peculiar way.

00:06:59.750 --> 00:07:04.040
The net result is I never once
thought about becoming a chef.

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:05.630
I never once thought
about being

00:07:05.630 --> 00:07:08.450
passionate about cooking.

00:07:08.450 --> 00:07:11.870
And it never gave me any inkling
or idea about what I

00:07:11.870 --> 00:07:13.080
wanted to do with my life.

00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:15.050
And I hope that that's
OK with you guys.

00:07:15.050 --> 00:07:17.620
Because I think a lot of people
come to me and they

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:18.870
say, I'm passionate.

00:07:22.140 --> 00:07:23.840
And I say, cool.

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:25.430
I might not be today.

00:07:29.110 --> 00:07:31.760
I know this is this big moment
where there's a payoff for you

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:34.020
as an audience, where I say to
you all this stuff happened,

00:07:34.020 --> 00:07:35.520
and, oh my god, I
became a chef.

00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:38.460
And unicorns flew out
of the refrigerator.

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:40.600
And there were rainbows
and star decals.

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:42.580
And I got a gold medal
and whatever.

00:07:42.580 --> 00:07:45.880
No, actually, zero
of that happened.

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:50.360
When I went to college, I ate
a lot of Rice-A-Roni.

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:51.450
Good stuff, by the way.

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:52.500
Don't tell anybody.

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:54.200
FEMALE SPEAKER: You know
this is Google.

00:07:54.200 --> 00:07:55.660
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Go to
Google and tell secrets.

00:07:55.660 --> 00:07:58.450
Good idea.

00:07:58.450 --> 00:08:00.530
So I made a lot of cakes.

00:08:00.530 --> 00:08:02.520
It was, like, dude, so-and-so's
birthday, can you

00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:03.120
make a cake?

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:04.310
And I just liked doing it.

00:08:04.310 --> 00:08:04.950
I just did it.

00:08:04.950 --> 00:08:09.330
I made these pans of lasagna
with shoplifted pieces of

00:08:09.330 --> 00:08:10.130
mozzarella.

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:13.230
That stuff's expensive.

00:08:13.230 --> 00:08:16.080
And I just cooked a lot, but in
that kind of random college

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:18.150
way like, dude, I made
some ramen and I put

00:08:18.150 --> 00:08:18.810
a bay leaf in it.

00:08:18.810 --> 00:08:20.060
It's good.

00:08:23.150 --> 00:08:27.550
So, again, I get back to this
idea that I was steeped in

00:08:27.550 --> 00:08:29.440
food the whole time, and
I'm disorganized.

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:30.680
And I didn't make
the connection.

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:33.330
But when I woke up on graduation
day, I thought I'm

00:08:33.330 --> 00:08:35.100
going to decide by the end of
the day what I'm going to do

00:08:35.100 --> 00:08:38.169
with the rest of my life
and that's it.

00:08:38.169 --> 00:08:39.610
So I promptly drank a beer.

00:08:39.610 --> 00:08:41.600
Because if you're going to
have a day like that, you

00:08:41.600 --> 00:08:44.770
should probably have
a beer at 9 AM.

00:08:44.770 --> 00:08:46.300
I had a couple.

00:08:46.300 --> 00:08:48.140
They were cold.

00:08:48.140 --> 00:08:49.240
There were good.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:51.610
That cheap beer, you know that
crappy beer that doesn't

00:08:51.610 --> 00:08:52.860
really have a label?

00:08:56.250 --> 00:08:58.560
So I graduated from college, and
I started working in the

00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:01.090
kitchen for free to kind of
explore this idea about

00:09:01.090 --> 00:09:04.080
whether I wanted to spend the
money on getting a degree in

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:05.760
cooking and whatever else.

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:07.930
And I never looked back.

00:09:07.930 --> 00:09:11.860
The disorder, the chaos, the
anarchy, the peril, the

00:09:11.860 --> 00:09:14.740
danger, the abuse, the
lack of skill--

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:19.240
all those things were just too
compelling to turn down.

00:09:19.240 --> 00:09:20.460
FEMALE SPEAKER: So it wasn't
so much passion.

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:24.550
It was just, sounds
like, destiny.

00:09:24.550 --> 00:09:30.280
Did you have another thought of,
you know, maybe I will be

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:31.730
a Spanish teacher.

00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:33.830
I mean, you have Napoleon.

00:09:33.830 --> 00:09:35.570
You've got someone who's
fluent in Russian.

00:09:35.570 --> 00:09:36.770
You're eating Indian food.

00:09:36.770 --> 00:09:40.430
Why not just go a completely
different route?

00:09:40.430 --> 00:09:43.280
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: No,
this has been my

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:45.190
dilemma with myself.

00:09:45.190 --> 00:09:47.630
I question whether you actually
can connect with your

00:09:47.630 --> 00:09:50.660
passion until you do something
so many times that you

00:09:50.660 --> 00:09:52.150
actually become really
good at it.

00:09:52.150 --> 00:09:54.180
And that, in fact, is when you
actually can say you're

00:09:54.180 --> 00:09:55.010
passionate.

00:09:55.010 --> 00:09:57.290
I think Roger Federer is
probably super passionate

00:09:57.290 --> 00:09:59.270
about tennis.

00:09:59.270 --> 00:10:00.850
You notice that?

00:10:00.850 --> 00:10:03.140
I'll bet you Al Pacino
is really

00:10:03.140 --> 00:10:05.140
passionate about acting.

00:10:05.140 --> 00:10:09.810
I think it takes a long time
to get good at something.

00:10:09.810 --> 00:10:12.350
And depending on your inner
struggle, I think it can take

00:10:12.350 --> 00:10:17.060
you even longer to think that
you're good at something.

00:10:17.060 --> 00:10:19.370
I'm still getting there
myself, without

00:10:19.370 --> 00:10:22.820
joke, a lot of therapy.

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:26.680
23 years of cooking and starting
to feel like I'm kind

00:10:26.680 --> 00:10:31.200
of getting the hang of
this cooking thing.

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:32.250
But I question.

00:10:32.250 --> 00:10:32.530
FEMALE SPEAKER: I think so.

00:10:32.530 --> 00:10:34.220
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI:
I think it's OK--

00:10:34.220 --> 00:10:36.600
FEMALE SPEAKER: I think
everybody here would agree

00:10:36.600 --> 00:10:38.260
that you've got the
hang of cooking.

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:38.560
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: No, no.

00:10:38.560 --> 00:10:39.810
That's sweet.

00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:46.610
I think it's OK to not be sure
if you're passionate, or be

00:10:46.610 --> 00:10:48.680
confused and decide later.

00:10:48.680 --> 00:10:50.650
But then you can get drunk at
a cocktail party and tell

00:10:50.650 --> 00:10:51.355
everybody you're passionate.

00:10:51.355 --> 00:10:52.010
It's cool.

00:10:52.010 --> 00:10:52.750
Like, get it out.

00:10:52.750 --> 00:10:54.240
Work it out.

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:55.650
Get on that emotional
treadmill.

00:10:55.650 --> 00:10:56.250
Let it out.

00:10:56.250 --> 00:10:57.110
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's kind of
when the passion comes out,

00:10:57.110 --> 00:10:58.160
after a couple cocktails.

00:10:58.160 --> 00:11:00.900
And you're like, I just love
ramen with bay leaves.

00:11:00.900 --> 00:11:01.880
It is the best food.

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:03.500
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: I mean, for
me, I call my fourth-grade

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:05.275
boyfriend and say,
I loved you.

00:11:05.275 --> 00:11:05.890
I did.

00:11:05.890 --> 00:11:06.810
I really loved you.

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:10.120
And his wife is like, he has
to get off the phone now.

00:11:10.120 --> 00:11:11.190
FEMALE SPEAKER: I think we're
going to have to bring her

00:11:11.190 --> 00:11:14.640
back for a whole different
interview about that.

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:17.690
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: And
I'm censoring as I go.

00:11:17.690 --> 00:11:18.770
FEMALE SPEAKER: Maybe we should
have had you drink a

00:11:18.770 --> 00:11:19.820
beer before you got up here.

00:11:19.820 --> 00:11:21.040
I didn't think about that.

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:21.300
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: No, no.

00:11:21.300 --> 00:11:23.420
Those days are over,
believe me.

00:11:23.420 --> 00:11:24.980
FEMALE SPEAKER: So, the book.

00:11:24.980 --> 00:11:26.230
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Yeah.

00:11:26.230 --> 00:11:28.330
FEMALE SPEAKER: First question,
did your mom help

00:11:28.330 --> 00:11:29.380
you edit this?

00:11:29.380 --> 00:11:34.420
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI:
No, not at all.

00:11:34.420 --> 00:11:37.480
She only saw the book after I
turned in the final revision

00:11:37.480 --> 00:11:38.630
to my editor.

00:11:38.630 --> 00:11:41.070
I left on the coffee table.

00:11:41.070 --> 00:11:41.730
What do we call it?

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:43.040
A dummy, a dummy.

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:45.500
So the manuscript, loose.

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:47.440
But color photographs,
assembled the way

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:48.280
it's going to look.

00:11:48.280 --> 00:11:50.800
So, in essence, it just
needs to be folded and

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:52.160
bound at that point.

00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:54.240
And I left it on the
coffee table.

00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:57.190
And I came home and my mom was
sitting there like a cat on a

00:11:57.190 --> 00:11:59.745
windowsill like when you've been
gone for three days and

00:11:59.745 --> 00:12:01.210
you didn't leave any food.

00:12:01.210 --> 00:12:04.040
That where have you
been bitch look?

00:12:04.040 --> 00:12:05.420
My mother gave me that
look and she

00:12:05.420 --> 00:12:08.140
said, I read your book.

00:12:08.140 --> 00:12:11.070
I said, you did?

00:12:11.070 --> 00:12:11.810
I left it.

00:12:11.810 --> 00:12:13.000
I cleaned the whole room
out and put the

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:14.734
manuscript on the table.

00:12:14.734 --> 00:12:18.160
I was like, you found it.

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:19.520
And she said, I really
love it.

00:12:19.520 --> 00:12:21.490
You're a real writer.

00:12:21.490 --> 00:12:23.160
So that was really cool.

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:24.380
And then she was like,
it better sell or I'm

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:27.150
going to freak out.

00:12:27.150 --> 00:12:30.760
FEMALE SPEAKER: So passion or no
passion, you have a career

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:31.870
that is larger than life--

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:36.520
Iron Chef, TV celebrity chef,
world renowned executive chef.

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:39.330
Why did you decide to write
a cookbook now?

00:12:39.330 --> 00:12:42.030
And what was your inspiration?

00:12:42.030 --> 00:12:43.190
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: You wouldn't
write a cookbook--

00:12:43.190 --> 00:12:44.720
I mean, you wouldn't direct
a movie if Steven

00:12:44.720 --> 00:12:46.440
Spielberg was your dad.

00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:48.310
So it took a long time.

00:12:48.310 --> 00:12:52.030
But I thought, you know, that
I had all these experiences.

00:12:52.030 --> 00:12:55.970
Interspersed throughout the book
are page stories that are

00:12:55.970 --> 00:12:59.680
just little isolated moments,
most of them pretty hideous.

00:12:59.680 --> 00:13:02.880
But some of them, I think, if
you're not a chef, but you've

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:05.540
had-- everybody works
in a community,

00:13:05.540 --> 00:13:06.880
in a group of people.

00:13:06.880 --> 00:13:08.610
Everybody fears failure.

00:13:08.610 --> 00:13:10.550
Everybody has moments
of vulnerability.

00:13:10.550 --> 00:13:12.940
And I think that that's
universal.

00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:17.410
And those stories that I put
peppered throughout the book

00:13:17.410 --> 00:13:20.210
are those kind of moments
the way I live them.

00:13:20.210 --> 00:13:22.140
You know, you live them
with a laptop or

00:13:22.140 --> 00:13:23.400
with a search engine.

00:13:23.400 --> 00:13:25.110
And I live them with onions.

00:13:25.110 --> 00:13:26.840
There isn't really
any difference.

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:28.650
I think we come up
against the same

00:13:28.650 --> 00:13:31.100
kind of internal dialogue.

00:13:31.100 --> 00:13:33.270
And I thought that I would write
about that and then in

00:13:33.270 --> 00:13:36.810
the interim give a lot of
recipes that are the

00:13:36.810 --> 00:13:39.250
culmination of a lot of things
I learned working in

00:13:39.250 --> 00:13:41.710
restaurants and recipes I
developed that just always

00:13:41.710 --> 00:13:44.410
work mixed with the stuff
that I really actually

00:13:44.410 --> 00:13:45.925
like to cook at home.

00:13:45.925 --> 00:13:48.340
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's the
question, so why did this book

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:50.160
focus more on the old-school
comfort food?

00:13:50.160 --> 00:13:51.680
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Yeah, I
didn't want to write a chef-y

00:13:51.680 --> 00:13:53.700
cookbook with dehydrated
ham chips.

00:13:53.700 --> 00:13:54.980
It's just not my style.

00:13:54.980 --> 00:13:58.360
I mean, I can make
stuff like that.

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:02.880
But I thought that I go to
a cookbook and I open it.

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:04.890
And I'll buy anything
anywhere.

00:14:04.890 --> 00:14:06.290
I don't care.

00:14:06.290 --> 00:14:08.910
I mean to say, I'll go to the
other end of the earth to buy

00:14:08.910 --> 00:14:11.980
an eye of newt to make
something specific.

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:15.155
But I'm attracted to and drawn
to cookbooks where I open it

00:14:15.155 --> 00:14:17.640
and I say, I can make a couple
of these recipes from what I

00:14:17.640 --> 00:14:18.950
already have at home.

00:14:18.950 --> 00:14:21.220
And I really wanted the book
to have that feeling.

00:14:21.220 --> 00:14:22.280
I think it's part of
being old-school.

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:24.620
It's like you're all
in a little ghetto.

00:14:24.620 --> 00:14:28.880
You've got that knife you won
because you were the ninth

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:30.620
customer at a gas
station one day.

00:14:30.620 --> 00:14:31.460
And you really like it.

00:14:31.460 --> 00:14:34.450
And you have these fancy knives
you got for Christmas

00:14:34.450 --> 00:14:37.570
two years ago, but you like
that crappy knife.

00:14:37.570 --> 00:14:41.420
You have a jar of oregano that
your parents brought you back

00:14:41.420 --> 00:14:43.890
from a cruise of Capri
six years ago.

00:14:43.890 --> 00:14:48.200
And you're wondering if the
oregano's still good.

00:14:48.200 --> 00:14:50.350
You wonder about the expiration
date of the baking

00:14:50.350 --> 00:14:51.920
powder in your cabinet
that you've used

00:14:51.920 --> 00:14:53.170
twice in eight years.

00:14:55.860 --> 00:14:57.130
I live the same way.

00:14:57.130 --> 00:14:57.950
I think we all do.

00:14:57.950 --> 00:15:02.650
And I wanted the book to make
you feel like you could live

00:15:02.650 --> 00:15:05.257
in that kind of context with
yourself and be imperfect and

00:15:05.257 --> 00:15:08.420
be human and cook, and make
some stuff that you like.

00:15:08.420 --> 00:15:11.370
Or just read it and not make a
thing, and tell everybody that

00:15:11.370 --> 00:15:14.480
you made every recipe
in the book.

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:15.500
You could do that, too.

00:15:15.500 --> 00:15:17.400
FEMALE SPEAKER: I may.

00:15:17.400 --> 00:15:21.520
I love that you focus on old
school, but what is your

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:22.970
definition of old school?

00:15:22.970 --> 00:15:24.320
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: I'm
glad you asked that.

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:27.040
For me, I looked
up old school.

00:15:27.040 --> 00:15:27.990
Because I like the term.

00:15:27.990 --> 00:15:29.240
I'm like, dude, that's
so old school.

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:31.380
And I'm thinking, what the
hell is old school?

00:15:31.380 --> 00:15:34.140
Well, I discovered that old
school for me is anything that

00:15:34.140 --> 00:15:35.580
I really like, period.

00:15:35.580 --> 00:15:37.190
That's actually my
own definition.

00:15:37.190 --> 00:15:38.700
I'm like, dude, that's
old school.

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:40.910
That shoelace is old school.

00:15:40.910 --> 00:15:42.120
It doesn't matter what it is.

00:15:42.120 --> 00:15:49.630
But I read that it is a moment
where you realize something in

00:15:49.630 --> 00:15:55.750
its original form serves as an
inspiration for you to explore

00:15:55.750 --> 00:15:56.680
new things.

00:15:56.680 --> 00:15:59.290
So I like the idea that you
could define old school by

00:15:59.290 --> 00:16:03.170
saying, like, that's
the OG idea.

00:16:03.170 --> 00:16:07.160
And then you can do all this
stuff, because it smacks of

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:08.930
that original feeling.

00:16:08.930 --> 00:16:11.980
And I think food is
so about feeling.

00:16:11.980 --> 00:16:13.010
It's about the weather.

00:16:13.010 --> 00:16:17.020
It's about whether you
had a crappy morning.

00:16:17.020 --> 00:16:21.460
It's about what you like to
eat, what you find, what

00:16:21.460 --> 00:16:22.570
resonates with you.

00:16:22.570 --> 00:16:26.000
I mean, I'm sure you all have
some food that you have, you

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.270
know, that no one but you
needs to understand.

00:16:29.270 --> 00:16:30.970
And you eat it.

00:16:30.970 --> 00:16:33.250
Probably have many.

00:16:33.250 --> 00:16:36.720
And that, really, by the way,
also connects to culture.

00:16:36.720 --> 00:16:38.010
How you grow up, what kinds of

00:16:38.010 --> 00:16:39.120
ingredients you grew up eating.

00:16:39.120 --> 00:16:43.010
Those are the tastes that
are familiar to you.

00:16:43.010 --> 00:16:44.940
And, again, I go back
to my childhood.

00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:46.440
It was very confusing.

00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:49.510
I have two Italian
American parents.

00:16:49.510 --> 00:16:51.290
My father's family's
from Naples.

00:16:51.290 --> 00:16:55.070
And my mother's family
is from Sicily.

00:16:55.070 --> 00:16:58.180
But my father cooked Chinese
food for a hobby.

00:16:58.180 --> 00:17:01.160
So we had this whole cabinet
of soy sauces.

00:17:01.160 --> 00:17:05.770
I mean, 80 kinds of soy sauce
and vinegar and corn starch

00:17:05.770 --> 00:17:09.140
and rice flour and woks.

00:17:09.140 --> 00:17:11.069
And then my mom was over
here baking cakes and

00:17:11.069 --> 00:17:12.290
making Indian food.

00:17:12.290 --> 00:17:15.569
I don't know what the food
of my childhood.

00:17:15.569 --> 00:17:20.089
I don't know how you would
define it, like disaster.

00:17:20.089 --> 00:17:24.190
But the net result was I felt
that old-school comfort food,

00:17:24.190 --> 00:17:26.560
it was sort of my way of saying
these are the things

00:17:26.560 --> 00:17:28.530
that resonate with me.

00:17:28.530 --> 00:17:31.050
And I tried not to make
it too hodgepodge.

00:17:31.050 --> 00:17:35.860
I mean, to have a souffle with
kimchi is sort of like, OK,

00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:37.490
who are you?

00:17:37.490 --> 00:17:38.770
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's actually
another question I

00:17:38.770 --> 00:17:40.540
had, is that the recipes are

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:41.790
diverse, but they're connected.

00:17:41.790 --> 00:17:45.260
And I'm just curious about how
you approached putting

00:17:45.260 --> 00:17:47.030
together, curating
if you will, this

00:17:47.030 --> 00:17:48.610
collection of recipes.

00:17:48.610 --> 00:17:49.410
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Yeah,
my mother cooked a

00:17:49.410 --> 00:17:50.320
lot of French food.

00:17:50.320 --> 00:17:52.800
She cooked from all of Julia
Child's books, and Craig

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:56.910
Claiborne, and Dione Lucas,
and James Beard.

00:17:56.910 --> 00:17:59.650
To just such a point where we
would sit down and my mom

00:17:59.650 --> 00:18:03.514
would say, Julia says this
tastes like this.

00:18:03.514 --> 00:18:08.115
And I'm like, mom, the padded
van is always parked outside

00:18:08.115 --> 00:18:09.580
if things get bad.

00:18:09.580 --> 00:18:12.610
But she lived and
breathed these--

00:18:12.610 --> 00:18:15.190
I'll call them characters
because I think that their

00:18:15.190 --> 00:18:21.040
recipes in their books sort of
added powder and made you feel

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:25.010
as if there was an actual person
or form that took shape

00:18:25.010 --> 00:18:25.960
in your own kitchen.

00:18:25.960 --> 00:18:28.930
So she lived with these
characters.

00:18:28.930 --> 00:18:34.340
And the food that I ate, I'd
have to say, was fundamentally

00:18:34.340 --> 00:18:36.030
French in technique
and in style.

00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:38.670
And I think that's why I ended
up going to France.

00:18:38.670 --> 00:18:42.810
Because I felt that that was
where I thought I could really

00:18:42.810 --> 00:18:45.360
learn how to cook, or build the

00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:46.890
building blocks of cooking.

00:18:46.890 --> 00:18:50.450
So the food here is actually
closet French.

00:18:50.450 --> 00:18:54.720
And then I hang American
things on it.

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:57.990
It's a French tree with
American ornaments.

00:18:57.990 --> 00:19:00.380
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's
kind of awesome.

00:19:00.380 --> 00:19:05.930
So in the book, there's
a line that I loved.

00:19:05.930 --> 00:19:07.830
It says you do not need a
well-stocked kitchen.

00:19:07.830 --> 00:19:10.590
Whatever equipment you gravitate
towards is what you

00:19:10.590 --> 00:19:12.320
should have.

00:19:12.320 --> 00:19:13.080
I loved that.

00:19:13.080 --> 00:19:15.680
Because people are like, you
need this and this and this.

00:19:15.680 --> 00:19:17.460
Or maybe it's just me being
like, oh, I want

00:19:17.460 --> 00:19:18.440
this, and I want this.

00:19:18.440 --> 00:19:20.230
And, oh, I should
have everything.

00:19:20.230 --> 00:19:21.930
But I love that it's like,
no, it's whatever

00:19:21.930 --> 00:19:23.260
you gravitate towards.

00:19:23.260 --> 00:19:24.360
For me, I guess it's
everything.

00:19:24.360 --> 00:19:27.030
But I'm curious, what do
you gravitate towards?

00:19:29.660 --> 00:19:33.740
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: My kitchen's
so embarrassing.

00:19:33.740 --> 00:19:35.830
I don't have a nice
kitchen at home.

00:19:35.830 --> 00:19:37.410
And I kind of like that.

00:19:37.410 --> 00:19:38.940
It kind of takes the
pressure off.

00:19:38.940 --> 00:19:41.980
I know this is where you think
I say I have a Viking and a

00:19:41.980 --> 00:19:43.360
Sub-Zero and all this
other stuff.

00:19:43.360 --> 00:19:44.330
And I actually don't.

00:19:44.330 --> 00:19:50.750
I have like a GE 1960s
thing, ovens.

00:19:50.750 --> 00:19:52.880
My mother had the same one
when I was growing up.

00:19:52.880 --> 00:19:55.840
So I think there's that.

00:19:55.840 --> 00:19:58.940
But what do I gravitate
towards?

00:19:58.940 --> 00:20:02.400
I probably have 200 or
300 knives at home

00:20:02.400 --> 00:20:04.240
in boxes and drawers.

00:20:04.240 --> 00:20:08.770
I mean, you've got to figure
that's normal, right?

00:20:08.770 --> 00:20:12.260
I mean, it feels normal to me.

00:20:12.260 --> 00:20:13.980
I'd been given many knives.

00:20:13.980 --> 00:20:15.880
I've been sent many knives.

00:20:15.880 --> 00:20:17.540
I've bought many knives.

00:20:17.540 --> 00:20:20.000
I've bought knives of people
that I've admired thinking

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:23.206
that if I had their knife,
I would be like we them.

00:20:23.206 --> 00:20:24.780
Do you ever do that?

00:20:24.780 --> 00:20:28.260
Like, if you put on a Superman
costume, you are Superman?

00:20:28.260 --> 00:20:32.100
Not if you get it at the Duane
Reade, probably not.

00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:33.440
So I have a lot of knives.

00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:36.130
And I like knives.

00:20:36.130 --> 00:20:38.970
But the ones I like are probably
the ones I recommend,

00:20:38.970 --> 00:20:41.640
the Sabatier, which
is like $6.

00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:46.000
That paring knife, honestly,
when I compete in kitchen

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:50.030
stadium on Iron Chef, I take
two of those with me.

00:20:50.030 --> 00:20:51.550
And I have one on either side.

00:20:51.550 --> 00:20:53.040
Because when you're nervous,
you know, you--

00:20:53.040 --> 00:20:54.620
it's like when you're
searching for

00:20:54.620 --> 00:20:55.870
a pen at your desk.

00:20:58.450 --> 00:21:00.455
If you have an important call,
I mean, I'm the type I'll put

00:21:00.455 --> 00:21:01.860
pens all over my desk.

00:21:01.860 --> 00:21:04.820
So that I'm like, uh-huh, I know
I can grab anywhere and

00:21:04.820 --> 00:21:05.690
there's a pen.

00:21:05.690 --> 00:21:07.420
This knife is like my Woobee.

00:21:07.420 --> 00:21:09.830
It's like the lioness,
like the blanket.

00:21:09.830 --> 00:21:12.220
So I have at least two of
those at all times.

00:21:12.220 --> 00:21:16.400
I like a microplane
grater a lot.

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:19.230
I think you can microplane
anything--

00:21:19.230 --> 00:21:21.590
not human beings, but
other things.

00:21:21.590 --> 00:21:23.250
I think a Vita-Prep blender.

00:21:23.250 --> 00:21:24.030
It's expensive.

00:21:24.030 --> 00:21:26.940
It's the one indulgence
I believe in.

00:21:26.940 --> 00:21:29.250
And then just that weird
accumulation.

00:21:29.250 --> 00:21:31.560
I like All-Clad pans a lot--

00:21:31.560 --> 00:21:34.530
not the fancy ones with the
copper this, that, the other--

00:21:34.530 --> 00:21:36.250
just that straight-up
stainless steel.

00:21:36.250 --> 00:21:39.960
And I like a cast
iron skillet.

00:21:39.960 --> 00:21:43.750
That's probably all I really
need to function.

00:21:43.750 --> 00:21:44.810
But, boy, do I have--

00:21:44.810 --> 00:21:46.565
I mean, I have a sea
urchin cutter.

00:21:49.240 --> 00:21:52.440
I have a quail egg crimper.

00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:55.000
I mean, I have boxes of stuff.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:58.396
And I open it up, and I'm
like what, like, really?

00:21:58.396 --> 00:22:00.870
I have eight different
cheese wires.

00:22:00.870 --> 00:22:03.670
What's wrong with me?

00:22:03.670 --> 00:22:09.010
But I in my actual kitchen, I
try to keep it to a dull roar.

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:11.200
FEMALE SPEAKER: I can only
imagine what kind of roars

00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:13.460
come out of that kitchen.

00:22:13.460 --> 00:22:17.850
So writing this cookbook, I
always like to ask-- maybe not

00:22:17.850 --> 00:22:19.660
passion, but discovery--

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:21.480
so what was your favorite
discovery?

00:22:21.480 --> 00:22:27.240
Or a strong moment you had
during the writing this book,

00:22:27.240 --> 00:22:28.670
the creation of this book?

00:22:28.670 --> 00:22:29.180
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: I didn't.

00:22:29.180 --> 00:22:30.890
I don't think I had any.

00:22:30.890 --> 00:22:31.460
