00:41:56.770 --> 00:41:59.420
It was the second and the
third and the fourth 500

00:41:59.420 --> 00:42:02.900
pounds of pico de gallo that
got a little boring.

00:42:02.900 --> 00:42:06.330
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: I think
that I am perpetually

00:42:06.330 --> 00:42:09.060
stimulated by repetition.

00:42:09.060 --> 00:42:11.620
That's something I know about
myself that I learned.

00:42:11.620 --> 00:42:14.370
I like cooking the same things
again and again.

00:42:14.370 --> 00:42:16.180
I like that feeling.

00:42:16.180 --> 00:42:18.150
I like the process.

00:42:18.150 --> 00:42:22.730
I'd say that's something that
would definitely make you lose

00:42:22.730 --> 00:42:25.060
your way if that wasn't
of interest to you.

00:42:25.060 --> 00:42:28.640
I don't think a lot of people
realize that, that cooking is

00:42:28.640 --> 00:42:30.380
a manual craft.

00:42:30.380 --> 00:42:31.080
It's manual.

00:42:31.080 --> 00:42:32.220
It's manual labor.

00:42:32.220 --> 00:42:35.560
And it does involve lots
of repetition.

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:39.210
But I feel like as you're honing
your skills, where your

00:42:39.210 --> 00:42:42.070
learning to dice all the
vegetables to make a good pico

00:42:42.070 --> 00:42:45.820
de gallo and you're learning how
to cook beans, I presume

00:42:45.820 --> 00:42:49.660
you could add certain things,
like learn about epazote as

00:42:49.660 --> 00:42:52.530
something that you use to
cook black beans, how to

00:42:52.530 --> 00:42:53.620
cook them just so.

00:42:53.620 --> 00:42:57.190
All the different skills that
are used to make a good pico

00:42:57.190 --> 00:43:00.860
de gallo are skills that you
then take and turn around and

00:43:00.860 --> 00:43:04.850
use to make so many hundreds
of other dishes.

00:43:04.850 --> 00:43:08.400
That I worry that he doesn't
see sort of the value in

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:11.770
developing a skill set that he
can then use to do things he

00:43:11.770 --> 00:43:14.990
really does feel personally
passionate about making.

00:43:14.990 --> 00:43:18.470
I would say you have to work
in the type of restaurant

00:43:18.470 --> 00:43:21.400
where the food resonates
with you.

00:43:21.400 --> 00:43:24.210
I went to a restaurant where
I like the food.

00:43:24.210 --> 00:43:25.570
And I like what was
being made.

00:43:25.570 --> 00:43:26.690
I liked the way it tasted.

00:43:26.690 --> 00:43:29.450
I wanted to know how those
things came to be.

00:43:29.450 --> 00:43:31.580
And I think if you're not
careful about that choice--

00:43:31.580 --> 00:43:33.020
because you're not going to make
a lot of money when you

00:43:33.020 --> 00:43:35.000
start out no matter what,
you may as well be

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:36.830
broke and do some like.

00:43:36.830 --> 00:43:37.950
I mean, really.

00:43:37.950 --> 00:43:41.360
So I think maybe he shouldn't
work in a restaurant where

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:44.180
they make pico de gallo and
should work in a restaurant

00:43:44.180 --> 00:43:47.060
where they cook and use
ingredients that he does find

00:43:47.060 --> 00:43:48.600
stimulating.

00:43:48.600 --> 00:43:50.160
And then he should also
cook at home.

00:43:50.160 --> 00:43:53.260
And he should read maybe some
cookbooks and Google some

00:43:53.260 --> 00:43:58.030
recipes and do all sorts of
other things to kind of put

00:43:58.030 --> 00:44:01.880
his own wood in his own fire
and not focus so much on

00:44:01.880 --> 00:44:02.160
[INAUDIBLE].

00:44:02.160 --> 00:44:04.400
Because cooking is
all repetition.

00:44:04.400 --> 00:44:06.255
If he doesn't like the
repetition, I don't know that

00:44:06.255 --> 00:44:07.490
he'll ever--

00:44:07.490 --> 00:44:10.690
maybe a professional kitchen
is not the place for him in

00:44:10.690 --> 00:44:12.240
the field of cooking.

00:44:12.240 --> 00:44:15.500
Food styling for cookbooks,
for photography shoots for

00:44:15.500 --> 00:44:19.200
magazines, catering, jobs where
there are restaurants

00:44:19.200 --> 00:44:21.000
where the menu changes
every day.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:22.810
And there are different
ingredients being used.

00:44:22.810 --> 00:44:24.440
He's just not in the
right place.

00:44:24.440 --> 00:44:27.440
AUDIENCE: And nutrition and
working with food companies, I

00:44:27.440 --> 00:44:30.480
mean he understands those
career options, too.

00:44:30.480 --> 00:44:31.860
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: It doesn't
matter what you understand

00:44:31.860 --> 00:44:35.520
about career options with
a field like cooking.

00:44:35.520 --> 00:44:38.270
You have to figure out what you
actually want to spend all

00:44:38.270 --> 00:44:41.180
those hours doing
with your time.

00:44:41.180 --> 00:44:44.430
And then when you hit on the
right thing, then you're not

00:44:44.430 --> 00:44:45.560
broke anymore, either.

00:44:45.560 --> 00:44:47.630
You're not rich,
but you're OK.

00:44:47.630 --> 00:44:49.290
That comes after.

00:44:49.290 --> 00:44:54.200
And those kind of reversals that
I think don't exist in

00:44:54.200 --> 00:44:57.450
the same way in a lot of other
fields can be very confusing.

00:44:57.450 --> 00:44:58.390
FEMALE SPEAKER: Interesting.

00:44:58.390 --> 00:44:59.550
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:59.550 --> 00:45:00.070
FEMALE SPEAKER: Question
over there.

00:45:00.070 --> 00:45:00.920
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Tell
him he should be a

00:45:00.920 --> 00:45:03.850
chef, goddamn it.

00:45:03.850 --> 00:45:04.230
Hi.

00:45:04.230 --> 00:45:06.220
AUDIENCE: Yes, hi, Chef
Guarnaschelli.

00:45:06.220 --> 00:45:06.540
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Hi.

00:45:06.540 --> 00:45:07.500
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:45:07.500 --> 00:45:08.340
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Sure.

