00:46:23.030 --> 00:46:30.160
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so a standard
cook would probably cook in a

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:31.290
restaurant, OK?

00:46:31.290 --> 00:46:34.990
But you're like on television
and "Chopped" and "Iron Chef."

00:46:34.990 --> 00:46:37.500
Can you describe exactly how
you got into that industry?

00:46:37.500 --> 00:46:41.260
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI: Oh,
yeah, I wish I knew.

00:46:41.260 --> 00:46:44.100
I really wanted to be a
competitor on "Iron Chef

00:46:44.100 --> 00:46:47.960
America." I watched "Iron
Chef." I still do.

00:46:47.960 --> 00:46:51.440
And I liked the way it's a
show that focuses on one

00:46:51.440 --> 00:46:54.660
single ingredient and where
people take it.

00:46:54.660 --> 00:46:56.430
And I just thought it was
the coolest thing.

00:46:56.430 --> 00:46:59.100
And I had this fantasy that
Iron Chefs were like

00:46:59.100 --> 00:47:00.660
superheroes.

00:47:00.660 --> 00:47:05.470
You know, there's Aquaman and
there's Wonder Woman.

00:47:05.470 --> 00:47:09.490
It sort of was my own personal
chef iconography, I

00:47:09.490 --> 00:47:12.110
think, of some kind.

00:47:12.110 --> 00:47:14.820
So I really wanted to be on
that show as a competitor.

00:47:14.820 --> 00:47:20.930
So that took me a couple years
to get that opportunity

00:47:20.930 --> 00:47:24.890
through begging and pleading,
and went on the show and

00:47:24.890 --> 00:47:28.940
realized that day that I
probably couldn't joke and

00:47:28.940 --> 00:47:32.130
banter and be myself and
express and share my

00:47:32.130 --> 00:47:36.600
personality and also
win the episode.

00:47:36.600 --> 00:47:40.930
I made that call that morning.

00:47:40.930 --> 00:47:44.350
I remember thinking you
can't do both these.

00:47:44.350 --> 00:47:45.570
Maybe some people can.

00:47:45.570 --> 00:47:46.150
I can't.

00:47:46.150 --> 00:47:48.230
And I knew that I couldn't.

00:47:48.230 --> 00:47:50.270
And when you have a lucid moment
about yourself, you

00:47:50.270 --> 00:47:51.410
should probably go with it.

00:47:51.410 --> 00:47:52.910
And I made a choice
that morning.

00:47:52.910 --> 00:47:55.130
I thought, well, OK, so I won't
worry about winning.

00:47:55.130 --> 00:47:57.070
I'll make the best food I can.

00:47:57.070 --> 00:47:59.370
I'll express my personal
side as best I can.

00:47:59.370 --> 00:48:01.710
And I want to share
my personality.

00:48:01.710 --> 00:48:06.350
And I think that wound
up being effective.

00:48:06.350 --> 00:48:09.870
I got asked to be on "Food
Network Challenge" after that.

00:48:09.870 --> 00:48:12.520
And then they did the screen
test where I had to make a

00:48:12.520 --> 00:48:16.210
minestrone, a basic minestrone
with tomatoes and beans and

00:48:16.210 --> 00:48:17.110
vegetables.

00:48:17.110 --> 00:48:19.760
So they put the camera on me
in this little room at the

00:48:19.760 --> 00:48:20.190
Food Network.

00:48:20.190 --> 00:48:21.180
And I made the minestrone.

00:48:21.180 --> 00:48:22.060
And I cooked the whole thing.

00:48:22.060 --> 00:48:22.495
And I explained.

00:48:22.495 --> 00:48:23.380
And I smiled.

00:48:23.380 --> 00:48:24.930
And I did all this stuff.

00:48:24.930 --> 00:48:27.780
And I finished the soup, and I
looked down and she said, you

00:48:27.780 --> 00:48:30.550
forgot the tomatoes.

00:48:30.550 --> 00:48:33.720
And I thought, well,
this is a bust.

00:48:33.720 --> 00:48:35.990
I mean, it's like pizza
without cheese.

00:48:35.990 --> 00:48:38.900
How's it going?

00:48:38.900 --> 00:48:41.250
But then they said, you know,
you're really good.

00:48:41.250 --> 00:48:42.480
We can work with this.

00:48:42.480 --> 00:48:45.640
And I did "The Cooking Loft,"
which was my first cooking

00:48:45.640 --> 00:48:48.100
show, which was really awful.

00:48:48.100 --> 00:48:49.410
And I really didn't
like the show.

00:48:49.410 --> 00:48:51.720
So they said, do you want to
make more of this show?

00:48:51.720 --> 00:48:55.030
And I said, I'd rather not be
on television than make this

00:48:55.030 --> 00:48:56.640
show because I don't like it.

00:48:56.640 --> 00:48:59.580
And I think that's a really
important moment there, where

00:48:59.580 --> 00:49:02.800
I walked away from something
that I was really starting to

00:49:02.800 --> 00:49:06.340
like because I didn't think it
was good enough for my own

00:49:06.340 --> 00:49:07.940
personal internal set
of standards.

00:49:07.940 --> 00:49:12.960
And Bobby Flay kind of got
assigned to my case maybe a

00:49:12.960 --> 00:49:15.950
year later to produce a
cooking show for me.

00:49:15.950 --> 00:49:17.950
And I made "Alex's Day
Off." And that was a

00:49:17.950 --> 00:49:18.850
whole different ballgame.

00:49:18.850 --> 00:49:21.040
He said, wear the clothes
you want to wear.

00:49:21.040 --> 00:49:22.470
Say what you want to say.

00:49:22.470 --> 00:49:23.230
Cook what you want to cook.

00:49:23.230 --> 00:49:25.760
And I said, really?

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:28.300
That's what--

00:49:28.300 --> 00:49:29.080
OK.

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:31.980
And the studio was right by
his house, his apartment.

00:49:31.980 --> 00:49:33.990
So he would come and drink
coffee with these mirrored

00:49:33.990 --> 00:49:35.580
sunglasses in the morning.

00:49:35.580 --> 00:49:37.160
And it would like fog
up his sunglasses.

00:49:37.160 --> 00:49:40.280
And he would stand there while
I was shooting the show, just

00:49:40.280 --> 00:49:42.190
looking at me.

00:49:42.190 --> 00:49:47.620
I mean, it was like being
watched by the police.

00:49:47.620 --> 00:49:53.660
And then they asked me to be
on "Next Iron Chef." And I

00:49:53.660 --> 00:49:55.310
really always wanted
to be an Iron Chef.

00:49:55.310 --> 00:49:56.430
And I'm a sucker.

00:49:56.430 --> 00:49:58.320
You know, I was like,
OK, I'll do it.

00:49:58.320 --> 00:50:01.470
How bad can it be?

00:50:01.470 --> 00:50:03.370
And it just kind of snowballed
from there.

00:50:03.370 --> 00:50:04.790
"Chopped" was an accident.

00:50:04.790 --> 00:50:05.890
They went to shoot the pilot.

00:50:05.890 --> 00:50:08.590
And I said I don't want to
be on that show at all.

00:50:08.590 --> 00:50:09.880
I'm sick that day.

00:50:09.880 --> 00:50:11.470
And they just hounded me.

00:50:11.470 --> 00:50:13.350
They just said, we think
you're right for this.

00:50:13.350 --> 00:50:15.940
We think you belong
on the show.

00:50:15.940 --> 00:50:17.260
I wasn't convinced.

00:50:17.260 --> 00:50:20.190
And so I hate to answer your
question by saying it's kind

00:50:20.190 --> 00:50:20.880
of an accident.

00:50:20.880 --> 00:50:23.810
But it was all born from one
singular idea that I was

00:50:23.810 --> 00:50:26.790
obsessed with being on "Iron
Chef America." And it

00:50:26.790 --> 00:50:31.480
snowballed accidentally and
became some strange avalanche.

00:50:31.480 --> 00:50:33.720
AUDIENCE: And you became
an Iron Chef.

00:50:33.720 --> 00:50:35.680
ALEX GUARNASCHELLI:
Yeah, totally.

00:50:35.680 --> 00:50:36.590
That's crazy.

00:50:36.590 --> 00:50:37.400
That never gets old.

00:50:37.400 --> 00:50:42.340
I get up every morning, I'm
like, I'm an Iron Chef.

00:50:42.340 --> 00:50:44.150
I'm like, on my tombstone,
I'm going to write Mom,

00:50:44.150 --> 00:50:45.090
Daughter, Iron Chef.

00:50:45.090 --> 00:50:47.300
This is so cool.

00:50:47.300 --> 00:50:49.120
When the curtain dropped and
my face was there, I

00:50:49.120 --> 00:50:52.030
was like I can die.

00:50:52.030 --> 00:50:53.500
I never thought I'd have
a moment like that.

00:50:53.500 --> 00:50:54.840
I still can't believe it.

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:56.240
I have stars in my eyes.

00:50:56.240 --> 00:51:00.935
It's really hokey and sappy
and goopy and all true.

00:51:00.935 --> 00:51:01.440
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:51:01.440 --> 00:51:02.490
Thank you.

